# Core MVP Features

## 1. Desktop Application

LabForge will include a desktop application with a graphical interface.

The desktop app should allow the user to:

* Create a new deployment
* Open an existing deployment
* Enter company details
* Enter network settings
* Select deployment target
* Preview deployment plan
* Start deployment
* View deployment progress
* View deployment results
* Export deployment reports

The GUI should be simple and wizard-based for the MVP.

---

## 2. Declarative Configuration

LabForge will use a declarative configuration model.

The GUI generates a YAML configuration file, and that YAML file becomes the source of truth for the deployment.

The user describes the desired environment, and LabForge determines the steps needed to create it.

Example concept:

```yaml
company:
  name: "Acme Accounting"
  domain: "acme.local"
  netbios: "ACME"

network:
  subnet: "192.168.50.0/24"
  gateway: "192.168.50.1"
  dns: "192.168.50.10"

server:
  hostname: "DC01"
  ip_address: "192.168.50.10"

departments:
  - Accounting
  - HR
  - Management

users:
  generated_count: 10

features:
  active_directory: true
  dns: true
  dhcp: true
  file_shares: true
  baseline_gpo: true
```

---

## 3. Deployment Planning

Before making changes, LabForge must generate a deployment plan.

The plan should show:

* Target server
* Domain name
* Network configuration
* Roles to be installed
* OUs to be created
* Groups to be created
* Users to be created
* File shares to be created
* Group Policies to be configured
* Estimated deployment steps

The user must review and approve the plan before deployment begins.

---

## 4. Windows Server Configuration

LabForge will configure a Windows Server target by automating:

* Hostname configuration
* Static IP configuration
* Remote management setup
* Windows Firewall baseline
* Server role installation
* Required reboots
* Post-reboot continuation

The MVP assumes Windows Server is already installed on the target machine or VM.

Full unattended Windows installation is deferred until a later version.

---

## 5. Active Directory Automation

LabForge will automate deployment of:

* Active Directory Domain Services
* New forest creation
* New domain creation
* Domain Controller promotion
* DNS integration

After domain creation, LabForge will generate:

* Organizational Units
* Department OUs
* User OUs
* Computer OUs
* Security groups
* Administrative groups
* User accounts

---

## 6. DNS Configuration

LabForge will configure DNS for the new domain.

MVP DNS tasks include:

* Install DNS role if required
* Configure domain-integrated DNS
* Verify domain DNS resolution
* Configure server DNS settings
* Generate DNS validation output

---

## 7. DHCP Configuration

LabForge will configure DHCP for the organization’s local network.

MVP DHCP tasks include:

* Install DHCP role
* Create DHCP scope
* Configure gateway option
* Configure DNS server option
* Configure domain name option
* Activate DHCP scope
* Authorize DHCP in Active Directory

---

## 8. Organization Structure

LabForge will generate a basic company structure.

Example structure:

```text
ACME
├── Users
│   ├── Accounting
│   ├── HR
│   └── Management
├── Computers
│   ├── Workstations
│   └── Servers
├── Groups
└── Service Accounts
```

The MVP should support:

* Three departments minimum
* Ten generated users minimum
* Department-based groups
* Basic naming conventions

---

## 9. User and Group Generation

LabForge will create users and groups automatically.

MVP user generation includes:

* First name
* Last name
* Username
* Temporary password
* Department assignment
* Group membership
* Account enabled status
* Password change at next login

MVP group generation includes:

* Department groups
* File share access groups
* Basic admin group
* Workstation users group

---

## 10. File Services

LabForge will configure basic file sharing.

MVP file services include:

* Company shared folder
* Department shared folders
* NTFS permissions
* SMB share permissions
* Department-based access groups

Example:

```text
\\DC01\Company
\\DC01\Accounting
\\DC01\HR
\\DC01\Management
```

---

## 11. Baseline Group Policy

LabForge will create and link basic Group Policies.

MVP baseline GPOs include:

* Password policy
* Account lockout policy
* Windows Firewall enabled
* Microsoft Defender enabled
* Screen lock policy
* Basic audit policy
* Network drive mapping for department shares

The MVP should avoid overly aggressive hardening that could break normal use.

---

## 12. Physical Workstation Domain Join Support

LabForge will support physical workstations instead of creating virtual employee PCs.

The MVP should provide:

* Domain join instructions
* Workstation naming convention
* Recommended OU placement
* Domain join validation checklist
* Optional generated PowerShell script for joining a workstation to the domain

Example workstation naming:

```text
ACME-WS-001
ACME-WS-002
ACME-WS-003
```

Example generated script concept:

```powershell
Add-Computer -DomainName "acme.local" -Restart
```

---

## 13. Deployment Progress

During deployment, LabForge should show progress such as:

```text
Validating configuration...
Connecting to target server...
Configuring hostname...
Installing Active Directory Domain Services...
Promoting Domain Controller...
Configuring DNS...
Configuring DHCP...
Creating OUs...
Creating groups...
Creating users...
Creating file shares...
Configuring Group Policy...
Generating report...
Deployment complete.
```

---

## 14. Deployment Report

After deployment, LabForge generates a report containing:

* Company name
* Domain name
* Server hostname
* Server IP address
* DHCP scope
* DNS settings
* OUs created
* Groups created
* Users created
* File shares created
* GPOs created
* Deployment duration
* Success/failure status
* Errors and warnings

Report formats for MVP:

* HTML
* JSON

PDF can be added later.

---

## 15. Rollback and Error Handling

LabForge must handle failures safely.

MVP rollback behavior:

* Stop deployment when a critical error occurs
* Log the failed step
* Preserve logs
* Attempt to undo supported actions
* Restore Hyper-V checkpoint if using Hyper-V and a checkpoint exists
* Generate failure report

Rollback does not need to be perfect in v1, but failures must be handled clearly and safely.

